docs.abstract: The seven Twitter users had been blocked from interacting with the president’s account after criticizing or mocking him, a move that a judge ruled violated their rights.
docs.snippet: The seven Twitter users had been blocked from interacting with the president’s account after criticizing or mocking him, a move that a judge ruled violated their rights.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The White House has unblocked the accounts of seven Twitter users who sued President Trump for barring them from viewing or responding to his tweets, even as the administration has decided to appeal a federal judge’s ruling in May that Mr. Trump violated their constitutional rights.

headline.main: White House Unblocks Twitter Users Who Sued Trump, but Appeals Ruling
headline.print_headline: White House Unblocks Twitter Users Who Sued

docs.abstract: The event was originally meant to honor the Super Bowl champions. The president urged Americans to always stand for the anthem, without mentioning the team.
docs.snippet: The event was originally meant to honor the Super Bowl champions. The president urged Americans to always stand for the anthem, without mentioning the team.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump doubled down on his war with the Philadelphia Eagles on Tuesday, hosting a short celebration without the team as his spokeswoman accused the Super Bowl champions of turning their White House invitation into “a political stunt.”

headline.main: Trump Hosts Celebration, Without Philadelphia Eagles
headline.print_headline: No Eagles, Just the Anthem at the President’s 10-Minute Salute

docs.abstract: The Treasury secretary, Steven Mnuchin, has managed to stay in President Trump’s good graces while advocating a more free-trade approach, but that balancing act is showing signs of strain.
docs.snippet: The Treasury secretary, Steven Mnuchin, has managed to stay in President Trump’s good graces while advocating a more free-trade approach, but that balancing act is showing signs of strain.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Two weeks ago, Steven Mnuchin, the Treasury secretary, declared that the trade war with China was “on hold” and that the United States would temporarily holster its tariffs. The reassuring comments calmed markets and raised hopes that Mr. Mnuchin, one of President Trump’s most enduring and trusted advisers, was winning the internal trade battle that has gripped the White House.

headline.main: How Mnuchin Keeps a Steady Grip in a Tug of War on Trade
headline.print_headline: A Peacekeeper In a Trade War Led by Trump

docs.abstract: The legal memo takes an expansive view on the president’s authority. Lawyers argued that, as president, Mr. Trump has the power to end investigations.
docs.snippet: The legal memo takes an expansive view on the president’s authority. Lawyers argued that, as president, Mr. Trump has the power to end investigations.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump’s lawyers have for months quietly waged a campaign to keep the special counsel from trying to force him to answer questions in the investigation into whether he obstructed justice, asserting that he cannot be compelled to testify and arguing in a confidential letter that he could not possibly have committed obstruction because he has unfettered authority over all federal investigations.

headline.main: Trump’s Lawyers, in Confidential Memo, Argue to Head Off a Historic Subpoena
headline.print_headline: Trump Is Exempt  From Questions,  His Lawyers Say

docs.abstract: President Trump rails against undocumented immigrants as “murderers and thieves” who want to “infest our country.” Some of his opponents respond with rage.
docs.snippet: President Trump rails against undocumented immigrants as “murderers and thieves” who want to “infest our country.” Some of his opponents respond with rage.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump has railed against undocumented immigrants in recent days, branding many of them “murderers and thieves” who want to “infest our country.” Not long ago, he referred to them as “animals,” although he insisted he meant only those who join a violent gang.

headline.main: In Trump’s America, the Conversation Turns Ugly and Angry, Starting at the Top
headline.print_headline: Incivility Infests Life in the U.S. On Trump’s Cue

docs.abstract: On a visit to Nevada, President Trump delivered a blunt message he has repeated at rallies for weeks: “We need more Republicans.”
docs.snippet: On a visit to Nevada, President Trump delivered a blunt message he has repeated at rallies for weeks: “We need more Republicans.”
docs.lead_paragraph: LAS VEGAS — Leaving behind the chaos he sowed in Washington with his shifting immigration policies, President Trump visited his second midterm battleground state of the week on Saturday to deliver the blunt message he has repeated at rallies for weeks: “We need more Republicans.”

headline.main: Trump Appeals to Republicans in Las Vegas, Leaving Behind Washington’s Legislative Chaos
headline.print_headline: Leaving Legislative Chaos Behind, Trump Stumps for Nevada Senator

docs.abstract: Under President Trump, once stately medallions have gotten glitzier, and at least one featured a Trump property. Ethics watchdogs are worried.
docs.snippet: Under President Trump, once stately medallions have gotten glitzier, and at least one featured a Trump property. Ethics watchdogs are worried.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Since Bill Clinton occupied the White House, the commemorative medallions known as challenge coins have been stately symbols of the presidency coveted by the military, law enforcement personnel and a small circle of collectors.

headline.main: Trump Leaves His Mark on a Presidential Keepsake
headline.print_headline: Full of Splash, Trump Coins Set Off Boom And Bother

docs.abstract: The justices passed up an opportunity to take another look at whether the Constitution bars extreme partisan gerrymandering.
docs.snippet: The justices passed up an opportunity to take another look at whether the Constitution bars extreme partisan gerrymandering.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Supreme Court passed up an opportunity on Monday to take another look at whether the Constitution bars extreme partisan gerrymandering, returning a case from North Carolina to a trial court there for a further examination of whether the challengers had suffered the sort of direct injury that would give them standing to sue.

headline.main: Supreme Court Won’t Hear North Carolina Partisan Gerrymandering Case

docs.abstract: Foreign policy officials, including some in his own administration, fear a repeat of President Trump’s encounter with Kim Jong-un, the North Korean leader.
docs.snippet: Foreign policy officials, including some in his own administration, fear a repeat of President Trump’s encounter with Kim Jong-un, the North Korean leader.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump’s appetite for a meeting with President Vladimir V. Putin of Russia, his aides say, was whetted by his talks with Kim Jong-un, the leader of North Korea, two weeks ago. But it is precisely that encounter that is stirring unease among foreign policy experts, including some in his own administration.

headline.main: In Meeting With Putin, Experts Fear Trump Will Give More Than He Gets
headline.print_headline: In Russian Talks, Experts Fear U.S. Will Give Up Too Much
